\pard\li1574\sb17\sl299\slmult0\tx5212\cf1\b\f0\fs26 64\b0\tab\b A \i Guide to Church Pkintin\par
 The English Words word church is one of the most abused and misused words in the twentieth- century vocabulary.Unfortunate -\par
        ly, like Caesar, it suffers more at the hands of its friends than its enemies.Let's look at the four common uses that many Chris-\par
            tians make of the word church, some within and some without its proper biblical context.\par
            Building.Many people refer to the ouilding in which the congregation assembles as the "church." A man may say to his wife, "I am going down to the church to pick up my hat, which I\par
            left there after the morning service, " fully knowing that no other person will likely be in the building at the time he arrives. \par
                Denomination.It is quite common to speak of a collec -\par
        tion of churches which have assembled themselves together in some kind of organization or association as "the Baptist church," "the Methodist church," or "the Presbyterian church." \par
                Universal church.The universal church refers to all mem -\par
        bers of the body of Christ in all places and all ages.Some theolo -\par
        gians have referred to this as the "church invisible," but in actu -\par
        ality the church has never been invisible.\par
            Local church.The local church is a given geographical representation of the universal church.This usage of the word is most in focus throughout the pages of this book.\par
            Of the four common usages of the word church men -\par
        tioned above, only two are biblical.The first two have grown up in the jargon of ecclesiastical years.It is nor necessarily a great error to use the word church in these ways, unless by so doing one forgets the emphasis of the New Testainent\f2\emdash that the church is always people.The last two uses, universal and local, are the only scriptural usages of the concept of church; we will examine these further below.\par
           \cf0\b0\i0\f1\fs22\par

