\pard\li1425\sb221\sl230\slmult0\cf1\i\dn4\f0\fs20 The Greek Word\cf0\i0\f1\fs22\par

\pard\fi657\li1382\ri1199\sb134\sl244\slmult0\qj\cf1\up0\f0\fs18 The Greek word used in the New Testament to designate \dn4 either universal church or local church is \i\fs20 ecclesia. \i0\fs18 To the Greeks the word indicated an assembly of free citizens; however, to the Jews it had more theocratic connotations. In the New Testament the word takes three basic uses:\cf0\f1\fs22\par

\pard\fi748\li1300\ri1242\sb5\sl245\slmult0\qj\tx1377\tx1377\tx1363\tx1348\tx1348\tx1339\cf1\up0\f0\fs18 1. A \i\fs20 political assembly of free citizens. \i0\fs18 The word \i\fs20 ecclesia \cf0\i0\f1\fs22\line\cf1\f0\fs18\tab appears in this context in Acts 19:32, 39, 41. The English word \cf0\f1\fs22\line\cf1\f0\fs18\tab used in the Authorized translation is \i\fs20 assembly, \i0\fs18 which is quite \cf0\f1\fs22\line\cf1\f0\fs18\tab proper in describing the situation. God had worked various mira-\cf0\f1\fs22\line\cf1\f0\fs18\tab cles through Paul at Ephesus, and Demetrius, representative of \cf0\f1\fs22\line\cf1\f0\fs18\tab the silversmiths in Ephesus, expressed their fear that their patron \cf0\f1\fs22\line\cf1\f0\fs18\tab deity was in jeopardy because of the increasing number of people \cf0\f1\fs22\line\cf1\f0\fs18 turning to the gospel. In the confusion that followed, mob vio-\cf0\f1\fs22\line\cf1\f0\fs18 lence was averted by the speech of the town clerk. When the mob is in complete chaos (and when it is formally dismissed by the town clerk), it is referred to as an \i\fs20 ecclesia.\cf0\i0\f1\fs22\par

\pard\fi710\li1214\ri1338\sb24\sl245\slmult0\qj\tx1267\tx1257\tx1252\cf1\i\f0\fs20 2. Jewish assembly of the Old Testament. \i0\fs18 In his sermon \cf0\f1\fs22\line\cf1\f0\fs18\tab just before his martyrdom, Stephen speaks of Moses and "the \cf0\f1\fs22\line\cf1\f0\fs18\tab church in the wilderness" (Acts 7:38 Kjv). The word \i\fs20 ecclesia \i0\fs18 in \cf0\f1\fs22\line\cf1\f0\fs18\tab this context obviously cannot be a reference to the New Testa-\cf0\f1\fs22\line\cf1\f0\fs18 ment church but speaks in a general way of the congregation or \cf0\f1\fs22\line\cf1\f0\fs18 the gathering of Israelites in the wilderness under the leadership \cf0\f1\fs22\line\cf1\f0\fs18 of Moses.\cf0\f1\fs22\par

\pard\fi739\li1113\ri1381\sb30\sl250\slmult0\qj\tx1185\tx1171\tx1156\cf1\i\f0\fs20 3. The Christian church. \i0\fs18 Almost all other New Testament \cf0\f1\fs22\line\cf1\f0\fs18\tab passages deal with the Christian church in either its universal or \cf0\f1\fs22\line\cf1\f0\fs18\tab local form. Because of the extreme importance of this concept, \cf0\f1\fs22\line\cf1\f0\fs18\tab one cannot properly perceive of the doctrine of the church with-\cf0\f1\fs22\line\cf1\expndtw1\f0\fs18 out a thorough understanding of these two uses of the word \cf0\expndtw0\f1\fs22\line\cf1\i\f0\fs20 ecclesia. \i0\fs18  The  universal  church contains only true believers, \cf0\f1\fs22\line\cf1\f0\fs18 whereas the local church may include those who profess Chris-\cf0\f1\fs22\line\cf1\f0\fs18 tianity but who have not yet had an experience of regeneration.\cf0\f1\fs22\par

