\pard\li14\sb211\sl253\slmult0\cf1\expndtw1\i\f0\fs22 The Church Structures a Climate for Worship\cf0\expndtw0\i0\f1\par

\pard\fi681\li10\ri697\sb137\sl259\slmult0\qj\cf1\dn4\f0 A host of passages invites our attention to the subject of \cf0\f1\line\cf1\f0 the church promoting worship. It may be beneficial, however, to \cf0\f1\line\cf1\f0 confine our observation to the epistle of Ephesians. In chapter 1 \cf0\f1\line\cf1\f0 Paul immediately declares that the purpose of God's predestina-\cf0\f1\line\cf1\f0 tion and adoption is that His people might be "to the praise of \cf0\f1\line\cf1\expndtw2\f0 the glory of His grace" (NASB). Lest his readers miss the empha-\cf0\expndtw0\f1\line\cf1\f0 sis, the apostle repeats the worship theme in verses 12 and \expndtw-7 14. \cf0\expndtw0\f1\line\cf1\f0 The great benediction of chapter 3 also focuses on the concept of \cf0\f1\line\cf1\f0 worship as Paul writes, "To him be glory in the church and in \cf0\f1\line\cf1\expndtw2\f0 Christ Jesus throughout all generations, for ever and ever! Amen" \cf0\expndtw0\f1\line\cf1\expndtw1\f0 (Eph. 3:21).\cf0\expndtw0\f1\par

\pard\fi676\li10\ri678\sl262\slmult0\qj\cf1\up0\f0 To say that the church purposes to worship does not guar-\cf0\f1\line\cf1\f0 antee that the church fully accomplishes this objective. Providing \expndtw3 opportunities for believers to pray, sing, hear Scripture, read pub-\cf0\expndtw0\f1\line\cf1\f0 licly, or engage in any other kind of physical or verbal activity is just the beginning. As a matter of fact, worship is not primarily an \i activity \i0 but rather an \i attitude \i0 of heart and mind which com-\cf0\f1\line\cf1\f0 prehends God and rejoices in the realization.\cf0\f1\par

\pard\li9921\sl253\slmult0\fs24\par

\pard\li14\sb155\sl253\slmult0\cf1\expndtw1\i\f0\fs22 The Church Provides the Setting for Fellowship\cf0\expndtw0\i0\f1\par

\pard\fi672\li14\ri587\sb131\sl270\slmult0\qj\cf1\f0 A little phrase in Ephesians \dn4 3:18 is often overlooked: \cf0\f1\line\cf1\f0 "with all the saints." These words speak volumes regarding the \cf0\f1\line\cf1\up4\f0 nature of the church. Isolationism has never been God's way, and \cf0\f1\line\cf1\f0 biblical separation today should be interpreted neither as \i isola-\cf0\i0\f1\line\cf1\i\f0 tion \i0 from others nor as \i insulation \i0 from the very world that needs \cf0\f1\line\cf1\f0 the witness of the church. The apostle John writes of fellowship \cf0\f1\line\cf1\f0 in his first epistle: "What we have seen and heard we proclaim to \cf0\f1\line\cf1\f0 you also, so that you too may have fellowship with us; and \cf0\f1\line\cf1\f0 indeed our fellowship is with the Father, and with His Son Jesus \cf0\f1\line\cf1\f0 Christ" (1 John 1:3 \fs18 NASB). \fs22 In other words, horizontal fellowship \cf0\f1\line\cf1\f0 among God's people depends upon vertical fellows\super\fs33 hip between \cf0\nosupersub\f1\fs22\line\cf1\f0 individual Christians and their Lord. The world must s\super\fs33 ee Chris-\cf0\nosupersub\f1\fs22\par

