\pard\fi230\li3576\ri3273\sb17\sl287\slmult0\cf1\b\f0\fs18 TEAM LEADERSHIP \cf0\b0\f1\fs22\line\cf1\expndtw-1\b\f0\fs18 IN CHRISTIAN MINISTRY\cf0\expndtw0\b0\f1\fs22\par

\pard\li1617\sl266\slmult0\fs24\par

\pard\fi696\li1617\ri1319\sb84\sl266\slmult0\qj\cf1\f0\fs22 One writer draws from these Scriptures five principles that speak to the relationship of believers in community as they seek to worship and serve God together:\cf0\f1\par

\pard\li1689\sl235\slmult0\fs24\par

\pard\li2351\ri1334\sb29\sl235\slmult0\qj\tx2563\cf1\f0\fs18 1. \fs20 The priesthood of the believer must be held in healthy ten-\cf0\f1\fs22\line\cf1\f0\fs20\tab sion with other basic concepts; it is not an absolute.\cf0\f1\fs22\par

\pard\li2347\sl225\slmult0\cf1\f0\fs20 2. The believer can delegate some of the authority of his life\cf0\f1\fs22\par

\pard\li2572\sb1\sl225\slmult0\cf1\f0\fs20 and ministry to other believers.\cf0\f1\fs22\par

\pard\li2361\ri1334\sb1\sl230\slmult0\qj\tx2582\cf1\f0\fs20 3. The priesthood of the believer is conditioned by the gifts and \cf0\f1\fs22\line\cf1\f0\fs20\tab\expndtw2\dn4 roles in the life of the fellowship.\cf0\expndtw0\f1\fs22\par

\pard\li2356\ri1334\sb6\sl225\slmult0\qj\tx2582\cf1\b\up0\f0\fs20 4. \b0 The priesthood of the believer implies shared responsibility \cf0\f1\fs22\line\cf1\f0\fs20\tab and ministry as well as shared authority.\cf0\f1\fs22\par

\pard\li2371\ri1338\sb1\sl225\slmult0\qj\tx2596\cf1\f0\fs20 S. The priesthood of the believer is the basis for decision mak-\cf0\f1\fs22\line\cf1\f0\fs20\tab\expndtw1 ing in the church.3\cf0\expndtw0\f1\fs22\par

\pard\fi686\li1689\ri1319\sb118\sl264\slmult0\qj\cf1\f0\fs20 Team leadership, commitment \fs22 to shared responsibility and authority, depends on a proper understanding of what it means to be the body of Christ. It emphasizes again the truth of being "laborers together," not only with God but also with each other, in carrying out the tasks of the church and establishing its witness in the world (Rom. 12:5).\cf0\f1\par

\pard\li3350\sl253\slmult0\fs24\par

\pard\li3350\sb131\sl253\slmult0\cf1\expndtw-8\b\f0\fs22 PAUL'S CONCEPT OF THE BODY\cf0\expndtw0\b0\f1\par

\pard\fi700\li1684\ri1339\sb151\sl264\slmult0\qj\cf1\f0 Perhaps no visual idea of the church receives more atten-\cf0\f1\line\cf1\f0 tion today than the image of the \fs20 body \fs22 described by Paul in 1 Co-\cf0\f1\line\cf1\f0 rinthians 12. On every hand we hear about "body life," "body truth," and the exercise of spiritual gifts within the body. This healthy emphasis will help us look again at corporate notions that the \fs20 early church \fs22 had of itself and at the \fs20 cardinal \fs22 principles that governed \fs20 its \fs22 life and ministry in the first century.\cf0\f1\par

\pard\fi700\li1680\ri1328\sl264\slmult0\qj\cf1\f0 Paul probably wrote the first Corinthian epistle from \cf0\f1\line\cf1\expndtw2\f0 Ephesus about \b A.D. \expndtw0\b0 57. A metropolis of the Roman province of \cf0\f1\line\cf1\f0 Achaia, Corinth was a great commercial center in the Mediter-\cf0\f1\line\cf1\f0 ranean world. Paul had visited the city twice and found it living \cf0\f1\line\cf1\f0 up to its reputation as a center of \super\fs33 sin and depravity. \nosupersub\fs22 Corin\super\fs33 th pre-\cf0\nosupersub\f1\fs22\line\cf1\f0 sented an enormous challenge to the gospe l. One could reason-\cf0\f1\par

