\pard\li2093\ri2819\sb278\sl283\slmult0\qj\tx2670\cf1\b\f0\fs18 UNITY AND COMMUNITY \cf0\b0\f1\fs22\line\cf1\f0\fs18\tab\expndtw-2\b IN THE BODY\cf0\expndtw0\b0\f1\fs22\par

\pard\li9412\sl270\slmult0\fs24\par

\pard\fi9\li110\ri827\sb91\sl270\slmult0\qj\cf1\f0\fs22 ably expect the principles of Christian faith to operate at Jerusa-\cf0\f1\line\cf1\f0 lem, where the members of the early church had been schooled for years in Old Testament truth. To motivate that kind of behav-\cf0\f1\line\cf1\f0 ior in pagan Corinth, however, presented unique challenges.\cf0\f1\par

\pard\fi739\li57\ri851\sb1\sl268\slmult0\qj\cf1\f0 Deplorable factions had split the Corinthian church into \cf0\f1\line\cf1\dn4\f0 hostile fragments. Some believers claimed to follow Paul, others \cf0\f1\line\cf1\f0 Apollos, others Peter, and some claimed such self-righteous piety \cf0\f1\line\cf1\f0 that they wished to bypass all contemporary leaders and refer \cf0\f1\line\cf1\f0 themselves directly back to Christ. Paul addresses a number of \cf0\f1\line\cf1\f0 the problems resulting from the schism that had drained both \cf0\f1\line\cf1\f0 unity and community at Corinth. In chapter 12 he makes an \cf0\f1\line\cf1\f0 explanation of the nature and use of spiritual gifts. Interestingly, \cf0\f1\line\cf1\f0 however, the bulk of the chapter does not deal with the specifica-\cf0\f1\line\cf1\f0 tion of gifts, but rather with the kind of people who \fs20 will \fs22 be min-\cf0\f1\line\cf1\f0 istering them. The \fs20 words \fs22 of the old hymn "Onward, Christian \cf0\f1\line\cf1\f0 Soldiers" well depict the intent of 1 Corinthians 12. They remind \cf0\f1\line\cf1\f0 the church, "We are not divided; all one body we, One in hope \cf0\f1\line\cf1\f0 and doctrine, One in charity."\cf0\f1\par

\pard\li9407\sl276\slmult1\up0\fs24\par

\pard\li52\sb108\sl276\slmult1\cf1\expndtw-5\i\f0 The Body Metaphor\cf0\expndtw0\i0\f1\fs22\par

\pard\fi686\li33\ri971\sb163\sl268\slmult0\qj\cf1\f0 Typically, Paul used common illustrations to explain diffi-\cf0\f1\line\cf1\f0 cult spiritual truths. First Corinthians 12 demonstrates in detail \cf0\f1\line\cf1\dn4\f0 how the unity of a \i\fs24 physical \i0\fs22 body offers a model for the kind of \cf0\f1\line\cf1\f0 unity that ought to radiate from Christ's \i\fs24 spiritual \i0\fs22 body. In verse\cf0\f1\par

\pard\fi38\li10\ri986\sb11\sl257\slmult0\qj\cf1\f0 13 the apostle points out that the baptismal ministry of the Holy Spirit places people into the universal body of Christ, the church. Most evangelical scholars agree that the treatment of baptism here is less likely a reference to the ritual act of water baptism than to the spiritual act of implantation into the body of believ-\cf0\f1\line\cf1\f0 ers. We should always remember that symbolical acts exist only to emphasize spiritual reality.\cf0\f1\par

\pard\fi681\li10\ri1024\sb65\sl268\slmult0\qj\cf1\up0\f0 The essence of this chapter is the old philosophical princi-\cf0\f1\line\cf1\f0 ple that "the whole is greater than the sum of its parts." Diversity \cf0\f1\line\cf1\f0 of parts characterizes the operating body, but unity and commu-\cf0\f1\par

\pard\sl180\slmult0\cf1\expndtw-3\f0\fs18 11\cf0\expndtw0\f1\fs22\par

\pard\sl240\slmult1\fs12\par
\par

\pard\li4036\sl292\slmult0\fs24\par

\pard\fi220\li3816\ri3353\sb170\sl292\slmult0\cf1\expndtw-8\b\f0\fs20 TEAM LEADERSHIP \cf0\expndtw0\b0\f1\fs22\line\cf1\expndtw-8\b\f0\fs20 IN CHRISTIAN MINISTRY\cf0\expndtw0\b0\f1\fs22\par

\pard\li1800\sl265\slmult0\fs24\par

\pard\li1800\ri1371\sb95\sl265\slmult0\qj\cf1\f0\fs22 nity of the members allow the body to function properly. Paul draws the argument to ridiculous extremes in order to make his point: "If the whole body were an eye, where would the sense of hearing be? If the whole body were an ear, where would the sense of smell be?" (v. 17). What kind of a functioning organism would\cf0\f1\par

\pard\li1852\ri1357\sl265\slmult0\qj\cf1\f0 one's body be were it composed of nothing but one giant eye? Or \cf0\f1\line\cf1\f0 perhaps one giant ear and no nose? Apparently autocratic leaders \cf0\f1\line\cf1\f0 already were manifesting their power in the early church. People \cf0\f1\line\cf1\f0 whose strong personalities overwhelm the body of Christ and \cf0\f1\line\cf1\f0 dominate its life and ministry have plagued the church from the\cf0\f1\par

\pard\li1900\ri1352\sl264\slmult0\qj\cf1\f0 first century. Such overpowering control by any one member, or by a select inside group, shows an inaccurate concept of the church and a failure to understand team leadership.\cf0\f1\par

\pard\fi715\li1920\ri1299\sl268\slmult0\qj\cf1\f0 After he focuses our attention on the functions of the physical body, Paul nails down the argument he really intends to make in this section of the epistle: God \i has a place for everyone in the church, and everyone's place is important. \i0 Remember the context of this passage\f2\emdash\f0 the use of spiritual gifts. Every Christian has a spiritual gift, and some may have more than one. And just \dn4 as all members have spiritual gifts, all members have distinct functions. God gifts people for carrying on the work of the church and then places them in the body for a particular purpo\super\fs33 se \nosupersub\fs22 of ministry. Not only that, but He does it in His own di\super\fs33 vine sov-\cf0\nosupersub\f1\fs22\line\cf1\f0 ereignty, just as He arranged the org\super\fs33 ans of the physical body to \nosupersub\fs22 create the best possible work ing relationship! Only when all members of the physical body d\super\fs33 o their tasks does that body func-\cf0\nosupersub\f1\fs22\line\cf1\f0 tion properly. The same is true \super\fs33 of the church.\cf0\nosupersub\f1\fs22\par

\pard\li1972\sl276\slmult1\up0\fs24\par

\pard\li1972\sb122\sl276\slmult1\cf1\expndtw-2\i\f0 The Broken Body\cf0\expndtw0\i0\f1\fs22\par

\pard\fi724\li1968\ri1275\sb115\sl274\slmult0\qj\cf1\f0 Ministry unity and \super\fs33 community break down when some \cf0\nosupersub\f1\fs22\line\cf1\dn4\f0 fail to exercise the ir proper gifts and roles in \super\fs33 the body, or when \cf0\nosupersub\f1\fs22\line\cf1\f0 certain members \super\fs33 are considered to be weaker or stronger, more \cf0\nosupersub\f1\fs22\line\cf1\f0 necessary or less n\super\fs33 ecessary. Mutual care in the body can eliminate \cf0\nosupersub\f1\fs22\line\cf1\f0 discord, but a \super\fs33 ruptured organ can destroy the entire system. An\cf0\nosupersub\f1\fs22\par

\pard\li5025\sb137\sl230\slmult0\cf1\expndtw-7\b\up0\f0\fs20 34\cf0\expndtw0\b0\f1\fs22\par

