\pard\li1887\ri2786\sb14\sl278\slmult0\qj\tx2455\cf1\expndtw-8\b\f0\fs20 UNITY AND COMMUNITY \cf0\expndtw0\b0\f1\fs22\line\cf1\f0\fs20\tab\expndtw-8\b IN THE BODY\cf0\expndtw0\b0\f1\fs22\par

\pard\li9695\sl254\slmult0\fs24\par

\pard\li10\ri890\sb107\sl254\slmult0\qj\cf1\f0\fs22 oversized gland creates abnormality, causing the entire organism \expndtw2 (or organization) to suffer desperately.\cf0\expndtw0\f1\par

\pard\fi672\li10\ri890\sb16\sl260\slmult0\qj\cf1\dn4\f0 In verse 26, Paul points out that the unity of the body is most apparent during a time of pain or suffering. A broken leg sends splinters of pain throughout the entire system. Even the common cold can simultaneously produce a runny nose, red and tired eyes, an earache, an aching head, a sore throat, an upset stomach, and general discomfort throughout the entire body. In the same way, all members of the spiritual body share the suffer-\cf0\f1\line\cf1\f0 ing and unhappiness of each other. Since a unified body enjoys community, when one of its members feels well or receives some particular benefits, the entire body rejoices. As Paul wrote in another letter, "Rejoice with those who rejoice, and weep with those who weep" \fs20 (Rom. 12:15 \fs16 NASB).\cf0\f1\fs22\par

\pard\li677\sb5\sl253\slmult0\cf1\up0\f0 The crucial application comes in 1 Corinthians \fs20 12:27: \cf0\f1\fs22\par

\pard\fi9\li20\ri894\sb12\sl259\slmult0\qj\cf1\f0 "Now you are Christ's body, and individually members of it" \cf0\f1\line\cf1\expndtw3\f0 (NABS). Note the emphasis on the word you. Even this fractured \cf0\expndtw0\f1\line\cf1\f0 Corinthian church, with all its doctrinal confusion and personal \cf0\f1\line\cf1\f0 bickering, could demonstrate the body of Christ to the world! \cf0\f1\line\cf1\f0 The "bookends" of this passage (vv. 12-27) fit classic Pauline \cf0\f1\line\cf1\f0 logic: "For even as the body is one" \expndtw2 (v. 12 \fs20 NASB) \fs22 and "Now you \cf0\expndtw0\f1\line\cf1\f0 are Christ's body" \expndtw-9 (v. \expndtw0\fs20 27 NASB). \fs22 Alan Redpath suggests that the \cf0\f1\line\cf1\f0 kind of unity Paul describes in this chapter "is only possible as \cf0\f1\line\cf1\f0 we recognize that within the church we have fellowship in our \cf0\f1\line\cf1\expndtw3\f0 diversity, as we learn to love and to care for our brethren who are \cf0\expndtw0\f1\line\cf1\f0 different, always recognizing the utter futility of identity."\cf0\f1\par

\pard\fi672\li34\ri889\sb9\sl255\slmult0\qj\cf1\f0 Francis Schaeffer wrote often about community. He emphasized that horizontal relationship can only follow vertical relationship because a Christian community can only be made up \expndtw2 of individual Christians.\cf0\expndtw0\f1\par

\pard\li10396\sl224\slmult0\fs24\par

\pard\li701\ri890\sb37\sl224\slmult0\qj\cf1\f0\fs20 Therefore, as we meet in our groups, we know who we are. We \cf0\f1\fs22\line\cf1\f0\fs20 are not like those who march in our streets and do not know \cf0\f1\fs22\line\cf1\f0\fs20 who they are\f2\emdash\f0 who call for community but have no basis for \cf0\f1\fs22\line\cf1\f0\fs20 community beyond biological continuity. Now we are ready to \cf0\f1\fs22\line\cf1\f0\fs20 begin real personal living, to practice the orthodoxy of commu-\cf0\f1\fs22\par

\pard\li12643\sl161\slmult0\fs24\par

