\pard\fi206\li3585\ri220\sb47\sl174\slmult0\qj\cf1\f0\fs12 Under Group A, the church ministries arc divided according to their \cf0\f1\fs22\line\cf1\f0\fs12 particular interest or responsibility. For example, the interests would be \cf0\f1\fs22\line\cf1\f0\fs12 adult and child education, outreach, training, music, missions, women's \cf0\f1\fs22\line\cf1\f0\fs12 ministries, and youth ministries. Within each of these interests, there is a \cf0\f1\fs22\line\cf1\dn4\f0\fs12 planning group, and with each group a church board member (deacon) \cf0\f1\fs22\line\cf1\f0\fs12 who relates to that group and communicates its needs and plans to the \cf0\f1\fs22\line\cf1\f0\fs12 church board. Some large congregations operate like this.\cf0\f1\fs22\par

\pard\fi201\li3561\ri292\sb78\sl171\slmult0\qj\cf1\expndtw1\up0\f0\fs12 Under Group B, members of the group are representatives of the \cf0\expndtw0\f1\fs22\line\cf1\f0\fs12 different major ministries \i and \i0 activities of the church. In addition, all the \cf0\f1\fs22\line\cf1\f0\fs12 deacons or elders and the treasurer are included. This seems to work \cf0\f1\fs22\line\cf1\i\f0\fs12 effectively in \i0 most situations. The whole church is fully represented and \cf0\f1\fs22\line\cf1\f0\fs12 no ministry feels left out and unimportant.\cf0\f1\fs22\par

