\pard\li317\sb138\sl138\slmult0\cf1\f0\fs12 Communication and Leadership\cf0\f1\fs22\par

\pard\fi62\li240\ri10\sb85\sl188\slmult0\qj\tx327\tx313\tx313\tx299\cf1\f0\fs12 Everyone is involved in communication. It is \i the \i0 process and art of \cf0\f1\fs22\line\cf1\f0\fs12\tab transmitting a message. Communication is made up of three essential \cf0\f1\fs22\line\cf1\f0\fs12\tab parts. First, the source person has an intent, or \i meaning. \i0 This may \i be \i0 an \cf0\f1\fs22\line\cf1\f0\fs12\tab idea, a feeling, or information. Then, there is the \i receiver \fs8 to \i0\fs12 whom the \cf0\f1\fs22\line\cf1\f0\fs12\tab meaning is sent The receiver is a person who has \i perceptions which may \cf0\i0\f1\fs22\line\cf1\f0\fs12 effect how he receives the meaning. When the communication process is \cf0\f1\fs22\line\cf1\f0\fs12 clear, the receiver understands the meaning exactly as the source person \cf0\f1\fs22\line\cf1\f0\fs12 intended. Here are some suggestions for helping your receiver understand \cf0\f1\fs22\line\cf1\f0\fs12 the message as you intend it:\cf0\f1\fs22\par

\pard\fi225\li187\ri59\sb85\sl184\slmult0\qj\tx241\cf1\f0\fs12 I. \i Understand and know what you wish to communicate. \i0 Have a clear, \cf0\f1\fs22\line\cf1\f0\fs12\tab objective idea of what you want to say, not just some hazy concept. If \i yea \cf0\i0\f1\fs22\line\cf1\f0\fs12 need to make a formal presentation or an announcement, write it out \i and \cf0\i0\f1\fs22\line\cf1\f0\fs12 practice saying it aloud so you have in mind exactly what you want to say. Make \i a \i0 habit of using notes \i and \i0 outlines.\cf0\f1\fs22\par

\pard\fi196\li144\ri130\sb85\sl184\slmult0\qj\cf1\f0\fs12 2. \i Know about the people with whom you communicate. \i0 The more you know about the receiver, the better you can \fs8 state \fs12 your message so he will \cf0\f1\fs22\line\cf1\f0\fs12 understand. If you know about his personality you will understand his \cf0\f1\fs22\line\cf1\f0\fs12 perceptions even better.\cf0\f1\fs22\par

\pard\fi235\li72\ri188\sb83\sl181\slmult0\qj\tx159\tx150\tx150\tx140\tx126\cf1\f0\fs12 3. \i Encourage continuous feedback. \i0 The term \i feedback \i0 originated from \cf0\f1\fs22\line\cf1\f0\fs12\tab electronics in relation to sound systems. It simply means the return of the \cf0\f1\fs22\line\cf1\f0\fs12\tab effects of a process to its source. in communication, this is the response. \cf0\f1\fs22\line\cf1\f0\fs12\tab Accepting feedback, or response, from the receiver will let you know \cf0\f1\fs22\line\cf1\f0\fs12\tab what he understands. This involves \i listening, \i0 which is an important part \cf0\f1\fs22\line\cf1\f0\fs12\tab\expndtw1 of communication. Listen in this case means to "Listen with full \cf0\expndtw0\f1\fs22\line\cf1\expndtw1\f0\fs12 attention." The church should not require a  "suggestion box" for \cf0\expndtw0\f1\fs22\line\cf1\f0\fs12 communication to flow freely. The pastor needs to maintain a climate of \cf0\f1\fs22\line\cf1\f0\fs12 healthy exchange and back and forth flow of communication.\cf0\f1\fs22\par

\pard\fi201\li19\ri294\sb100\sl167\slmult0\qj\tx78\tx73\cf1\f0\fs12 4. \i Use correct, precise language. \i0 Use exact terms whenever possible, \cf0\f1\fs22\line\cf1\f0\fs12\tab and not vague terms that may sound as though you want to conceal \cf0\f1\fs22\line\cf1\f0\fs12\tab something. Use words that the hearers will understand. They will not be \cf0\f1\fs22\line\cf1\f0\fs12 impressed by complicated terms that arc strange to them. Avoid terms \cf0\f1\fs22\line\cf1\f0\fs12 such as: a lot; a short time; only a few. If there is a problem, speak \cf0\f1\fs22\line\cf1\f0\fs12 directly and clearly to the person involved, not in vague terms to a group \cf0\f1\fs22\line\cf1\f0\fs12 which leaves the impression that some unknown person is at fault-\cf0\f1\fs22\par

